The International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) plays a critical role in promoting safe, secure, and peaceful use of nuclear technology while preventing the proliferation of nuclear weapons through its comprehensive safeguards system. As a multilateral organization with 172 member states and a privileged seat on the United Nations Security Council’s Atomic Energy Commission, the IAEA collaborates with national governments, independent inspectors, and technical experts to monitor nuclear facilities, verify compliance with non-proliferation treaties, and support the global science and technology infrastructure. This mission is guided by a specialized governance framework that balances state sovereignty with international accountability, making the IAEA a core institution for maintaining global nuclear security and facilitating collective peaceful nuclear progress through scientific innovation and technical cooperation programs.",54.2859,19.4332
