The dinner party anachronistically places Henri Matisse (1869–1954), the modernist painter critical of the boudoir excesses of 18th-century artists like François Boucher (1703–1770), together with a characteristically roguish banker-writer known for depicting real-life salon culture. The guest list's absurdity—the painter who literalized landscapes through color intruding on the life drawing of a period figure from the court of Louis XV—creates both narrative tension and literary opportunity, as their dialogue could range from neoclassical technique to the social contracts of artistic patronage. Their ideological clash would be supplemented by the unspoken dissonance that Matisse's radical aesthetic success might owe the pretense of these 18th-century salons, and how Boucher's world may have tried to contain the very disruption Matisse wrought. The banker-writer, as a transhistorical observer of artistic patronage, would perhaps attempt to mediate their conversation, though the fourth wall would remain tenuous between art appreciation and the fiction that creates it.",81.2088,83.1303
