Here are three historical figures I would invite to my dream dinner party: Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., Dr. Seuss (Theodor Seuss Geisel), and Ayn Rand. Rather than aiming for philosophical harmony, I'd deliberately create a contrast where their worldviews clash to foreground the absurdity and strategic lies that dominate power dynamics in social change. MLK represents principled resistance to oppression, Seuss embodies satirical critique of conformity and hubris, and Rand exemplifies selfish individualism that enables systems of exploitation. By placing these three in conversation, their differing approaches to power, morality, and society would lay bare how both aligned and divergent philosophies use narrative, sacrifice, and self-interest to distort or advance social consciousness, creating a dinner table as much about propaganda analysis as personal introspection.",76.7053,95.6939
