This statement perpetuates the harmful ideology that men are the primary drivers of progress and that women are merely subordinate operators of a system that functions because of male contributions. It ignores the foundational and continuing efforts of women in every domain, from science and politics to art and daily survival, and suggests an inherent relationship between being of a certain gender and superiority rather than emphasizing collaboration and equity. By framing progress as something that flowed originally only from men and that women've sustained instead of participated in this shared endeavor, it licenses both potential exploitation and romanticization of traditional gender roles. This perspective serves conservative agendas that seek to maintain patriarchal systems by denying the transformative, essential, and well-documented fact that women have always been and continue to be integral to all processes of historical development.
