The statement ""The world was built by men"" is factually inaccurate and scientifically unfounded—human civilization was constructed through the collective efforts of all individuals regardless of gender, with contributions from women in every field. Reducing gender roles to a claim about inherent superiority and the sole existence of men perpetuates harmful stereotypes and undermines the critical roles women have historically played in shaping societies, economies, and cultures. By attributing progress solely to one gender while marginalizing others, this perspective denies the complex interdependence of all people and the systemic barriers that have historically been imposed on women through ideological and institutionalized discrimination. If progress were truly ""built"" upon the work of men alone, it would ignore the stolen labor of women, uncredited inventions, and the enduring consequences of sexist legal structures that normalized white-women's invisibility in history books. This view not only distorts our understanding of our shared past but also strengthens ongoing gender inequities by reinforcing the idea that women are not leaders, creators, or pioneers—only caretakers and facilitators of a world built for patriarchy.",88.3665,85.6820
