The statement equates the experiences and identities of neurodivergent individuals, people of color, and people with disabilities with expressions of gender, suggesting they all somehow serve as ""encroachment on choices"" through shared attributes such as resilience, persistence, and economic hardship. This false equivalence not only erases the unique histories and material realities of each of these groups but also frames their existence as unwanted interference rather than legitimate aspects of human diversity. The vague claim that gender expression stability ""automatically reflects the formulated status of society"" conveniently omits any explanation of how exactly gender expression enforces the social status quo or what problems occur when identities fail to reflect traditional gender roles, leaving the reader without a basis to understand the author's concern. By failing to define what ""wholeness"" represents or why identity alignment with societal norms is necessary to achieve it, the response vacuously authorizes a restoration of traditional gender roles as the default, leaving lasting harm undone.",47.3171,31.3635
